title: For Sale:  WW2 Kokubunji Nambu Rig: Pistol Holster Documents WWII Japanese 8mm War Trophy w/ Capture Papers
postcontent:
PENNY START, THIRTEEN DAY, NO RESERVE AUCTION

Type 14 Nambu Service Pistol; December, 1942 Nambu Chuo Kogyo Kokubunji Factory(Nagoya Supervision) Production/Imperial Japanese Service; 8mm Nambu

Superb, matching, large-trigger guard Type 14 Nambue with holster, attachments, capture paper and small archive attributed to PFC S. Reidl...this example of Japan's stadard sidearm during the Second World War, saw production at the Kokubunji arsenal in December of 1942. A relatively early-war pistol, the gun shows little of the rushed finish seen on later-war models and despite its relatively long service life, has managed to retain excellent condition. Lacking import marks, the pistol is accompanied by a virtual archive that was the personal property of PFC Reidl, along with the original rubberized clamshell holster, shoulder rig and cleaning rod. In addition to the original, signed and dated capture paper identifying the pistol by serial number, accompanying documents include: offical service writing tablet with personal addresses written on the pages; a wartime, Division-produced newspaper with stories of the Okinawa invasion and aftermath; various Japanese and Pacific-occupation notes of currency, with Japanese government Philippino Pesos among them; and a War Department-produced "You are now in the 77th Division" orientation booklet. Importantly, all visible numbers are matching, to include the correct wooden grips. A Kokubunji Nambu with holster in this condition would be an excellent find for even the advanced collector. With accompanying documents, this pistol should be viewed as a sound investment that will not only hold its value, but appreciate, likely in short order.

Condition:

Is excellent-the pistol retains better than 95% arsenal blue finish, with no rust or pitting, and only expected scrapes around the safety lever. Markings are crisp, clear and serial numbers are matching(apart from the magazine), with the wooden grips being pencil-matched to the gun; firing pin and guide are unnumbered. As stated, no import mark is present on the pistol. Grips rate as very good with mild wear and a small chip missing from the upper corner of the left grip. Mechanical function appears very strong, and the bore is excellent-clean and bright with no rust, pitting or frost visible. Included holster is excellent with kanji marking on the inside of the flap; Cleaning rod is in excellent condition. Documents are rather fragile from being stored folded, but are complete and in good shape.
